 for bestpractices and # Email Verification

## Overview
This prompt guides the AI development tool to build a robust Email Verification experience integrated with transactional email workflows and a cohesive login/signup entry point. The system should securely process verification tokens, display clear verification status after signup, offer token resends, and guide users to the next steps (dashboard, profile completion). It must be resilient, guard against null/undefined values for array-methods, and adhere to the project’s design system, accessibility standards, and runtime safety rules described in the Mandatory Coding Standards.

## Page Description (Full Detail)
What this page is:
- The Email Verification page is the post-sign-up destination that shows the user’s verification status, processes any provided verification tokens, handles token expiry or invalid tokens, and advises the user on subsequent steps (e.g., go to Dashboard, complete profile, or contact support).

Goals:
- Accurately reflect verification state: pending (token just issued), success (token verified), expired/invalid (token invalid or expired).
- Provide a resilient flow for resending the verification email.
- Provide clear next steps CTAs and contextual help messages.
- Integrate with Email Verification & Notifications feature: trigger verification emails, digest emails, and alerts as appropriate.
- Maintain a cohesive UI with the Login/Signup entry point and SSO frontend as the authentication gateway.

UI elements and how they need to look:
- Status banner/cards showing: Pending verification, Verification successful, Token expired/invalid.
- Verification token processing state (loading indicator while validating the token).
- Resend verification button (with cooldown/visibility rules).
- Next steps CTA: Go to Dashboard, Complete Profile, or Return to Help/Support.
- Inline error messages and support contact options (email/phone) if verification fails.
- Small helper text and accessible ARIA attributes.

Connected features and API integrations:
- Token validation endpoint (verify token, userId, timestamp).
- Resend verification endpoint (issue new token, send email).
- Post-verification onboarding guidance API (fetch recommended next steps based on profile status).
- Email system integration: trigger verification emails and notifications (digest/alerts) as needed.

Visual guidance:
- Warm, calm aesthetic per brand palette; strong typographic hierarchy; consistent rhythm with ample whitespace; clear status emphasis.

## Components to Build
- EmailVerificationPage component
  - Props/state: userId, token from query params, fetch status, error messages, cooldown timer.
  - Subcomponents: StatusCard, TokenLoader, ResendButton, NextStepsCTA, HelpLink.
- StatusCard
  - Variants: Pending, Success, Expired/Invalid
  - Visual emphasis with appropriate iconography, color, and copy.
- TokenLoader
  - Spinner/progress indicator with accessible ARIA labels.
- ResendVerification
  - Button with cooldown timer, disabled during cooldown, success/failure toast messages.
- NextStepsPanel
  - Contextual CTAs based on user profile state (dashboard, complete profile, set up SSO).
- HelpPanel
  - Lightweight contact options (email/phone) and FAQ links.
- LoginSignupHeader
  - Reusable header integrated with SSO and Get started CTA.

Frontend tech specifics:
- Framework: React (with TypeScript preferred)
- State management: React useState/useEffect; consider lightweight context if needed
- Routing: React Router (or framework-equivalent) for token-based route (e.g., /verify?token=...&userId=...)
- API client: fetch or axios with proper error handling
- Accessibility: ARIA roles, aria-live regions for status updates, keyboard accessible controls

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend
- Pages and routes
  - /verify (Email Verification Page)
  - /login and /signup (connected via LoginSignupHeader)
  - Use query parameters token and userId for initial verification attempt.
- UI components
  - Ensure all components guard against null/undefined values before array methods.
  - Initialize arrays as empty: useState<T[]>([]) where applicable.
  - Always use data ?? [] for API responses returning arrays.
  - Guard against potential null data when mapping: (items ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(items) ? items.map(...) : [].
- Token verification flow
  - On page load, if token and userId exist, call verifyToken API.
  - Show loading state while awaiting API response.
  - If success: update status to Success and present NextStepsCTA.
  - If token invalid/expired: show Expired/Invalid state with guidance and option to resend.
- Resend flow
  - Resend button triggers API to issue new token and send email.
  - Implement cooldown timer (e.g., 60 seconds) to prevent spamming.
  - Show toast/inline message on success or error.
- Next steps
  - Detect user profile completeness and guide to Dashboard or Complete Profile.
- API integration (mockable in dev)
  - POST /api/auth/verify-token with body { userId, token }
  - POST /api/auth/resend-token with body { userId }
  - GET /api/user/profile-status?userId=...
  - POST /api/email/send-verification (or trigger via backend after verify)
- Validation
  - Validate token format length/structure client-side before sending.
  - Validate userId type (string) and presence.
- Error handling
  - Show user-friendly messages; log technical errors for analytics.
  - Provide contact support link if verification repeatedly fails.

### Backend
- Endpoints
  - POST /api/auth/verify-token
    - Input: { userId: string, token: string }
    - Behavior: verify token, mark user as verified if valid, return status and onboarding guidance.
    - Safeguards: idempotent verification; handle already-verified gracefully.
  - POST /api/auth/resend-token
    - Input: { userId: string }
    - Behavior: generate new token, save with expiration, enqueue transactional email sending.
  - GET /api/user/profile-status?userId=...
    - Input: userId
    - Behavior: return completion flags for profile, company data, preferences to tailor next steps.
- Data models
  - User
    - id, email, isVerified (boolean), verificationToken, tokenExpiresAt
  - VerificationToken
    - token, userId, expiresAt, consumed (boolean)
  - Profile
    - userId, isComplete, fieldsCompletedCount, onboardingStage
- Security
  - Token validation uses secure, time-limited tokens.
  - Authenticate internal requests with session or JWT as appropriate.
  - Rate limiting on resend to prevent abuse.
- Validation
  - Always validate input shapes; sanitize tokens; handle missing fields with clear errors.
- Email system integration
  - On verify success or resend, trigger transactional email events (verification email, digest/alerts as appropriate).
  - Persist raw payloads for audit as per project requirements.

### Integration
- Data flow
  - Verification page calls verify-token; backend updates user status and returns onboarding direction.
  - Verification status influences NextStepsCTA via profile-status data.
  - Resend-token triggers email workflow; on success, the UI shows a success message and cooldown state.
- Data safety
  - Always guard array/data handling with nullish coalescing and Array.isArray checks.
  - Ensure all API responses are validated: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].

## User Experience Flow
1) User signs up via signup form or SSO on the Login/Signup page.
2) After signup, user is directed to Email Verification page with a token in the URL (or token managed via session).
3) Page loads; shows verification status as Pending with a loading state.
4) If token is valid:
   - Verification succeeds; display Success state.
   - Show Next Steps: Go to Dashboard or Complete Profile (if profile incomplete).
5) If token is invalid or expired:
   - Show Expired/Invalid state with guidance.
   - Offer Resend Verification button (with cooldown).
   - Provide support contact options and retry guidance.
6) User clicks Next Steps CTA to navigate to the appropriate area (Dashboard or Profile).
7) System proactively triggers Digest/Alerts emails if applicable when status changes.

## Technical Specifications

Data Models: (Core structures)
- User
  - id: string
  - email: string
  - isVerified: boolean
  - verificationToken: string | null
  - tokenExpiresAt: string | null (ISO date)
- VerificationToken
  - token: string
  - userId: string
  - expiresAt: string
  - consumed: boolean
- Profile
  - userId: string
  - isComplete: boolean
  - onboardingStage: string
  - fieldsCompletedCount: number

API Endpoints:
- POST /api/auth/verify-token
  - Body: { userId: string, token: string }
  - Response: { success: boolean, status: 'verified'|'pending'|'expired'|'invalid', nextSteps?: string[] }
- POST /api/auth/resend-token
  - Body: { userId: string }
  - Response: { success: boolean, message: string, token?: string, expiresAt?: string }
- GET /api/user/profile-status?userId=...
  - Response: { isComplete: boolean, onboardingStage: string, fieldsCompletedCount: number }
- POST /api/email/send-verification
  - Body: { userId: string, email: string, token: string }

Security:
- Protect verify-token and resend-token routes with authentication context (ensuring userId matches session).
- Token validation should be server-side: compare token, check expiration, and ensure token is not consumed.
- Rate limiting on /api/auth/resend-token (per user/IP).
- Use HTTPS, secure cookies, and standard CSRF protections for state-changing endpoints.
- Do not leak token values in client UI beyond necessary.

Validation:
- Client: token length/format; userId presence; token presence when verifying.
- Server: strict schema validation; handle invalid payloads gracefully with 400 responses and helpful error messages.
- All array results from API calls must be guarded: (data ?? []) and Array.isArray(data) checks.

Required React State/Defaults:
- useState<string | null>(null) for token
- useState<boolean>(false) for loading
- useState<{ status: 'pending'|'success'|'expired'|'invalid'; message?: string }>(initial)
- useState<T[]>([]) for any arrays (e.g., potential nextSteps, error logs)
- Initialize arrays with []: useState<T[]>([]) and avoid useState() for arrays/objects.

